# Build Review Process

Adapted from a phased-build review framework, tailored for the Claude-assisted Salesforce team build model (Claude builds, humans refine and verify) and Salesforce declarative-first architecture.

**Scope:** This document defines how review is structured for every build session — agent-driven, human-focused, and config-only. It is not a waterfall gate at the end. Review is woven into each build mode using the right lens at the right moment.

**Relationship to other docs:**

- `docs/coding-standards.md` — defines _what_ standards to check against
- `/skill-preflight` — validates pre-conditions before a build starts
- `/platform-review` — quarterly deep review across 7 personas
- This document — defines _when_ and _how_ review happens during each build session

---

## 1. Review Dimensions (Salesforce-Specific)

Five dimensions, chosen for what actually breaks Salesforce builds.

### 1. Spec Compliance

**What it catches:** Implementation that doesn't match the design doc or backlog item spec — wrong field API names, missing flow elements, incorrect object relationships, stale references to retired components.

**Primary signal:** Discrepancy between the design doc (or backlog item notes) and what was built.

**When it matters most:** Start of build (does the spec trace to clear deliverables?) and end of build (did anything drift?).

### 2. FLS & Sharing

**What it catches:** Permission set gaps, missing FLS grants, overly permissive object access, sharing rule holes, Community user access to internal data.

**Primary signal:** A user can see or edit data they shouldn't, or can't access data they need.

**When it matters most:** Any build that adds new objects, fields, or permission sets. Any build touching Community-facing components.

### 3. Fault Handling

**What it catches:** Missing fault connectors on DML/action elements, silent failures in integrations, flows that fail without logging, screen flows that show blank screens on error.

**Primary signal:** A flow faults and the user/admin gets no feedback and no log entry.

**When it matters most:** Any build adding DML, callouts, or screen flows. Check against `coding-standards.md` Section 3 (fault handling standards) and the migration phase plan.

### 4. Test Coverage

**What it catches:** Missing FlowTests for agent-built record-triggered flows, Apex tests below 90% coverage, flow scanner violations, tests that pass but don't assert the failure they claim to cover.

**Primary signal:** A test passes but the bug it's supposed to catch would still ship.

**When it matters most:** Every agent-driven build (tests are generated alongside code). Human-focused Flow builds get flow scanner + manual verification. Config-only work gets org-query validation.

**Standard:** Verify assertions, not just pass/fail. Ask Claude to show the specific assertion, not just confirm the test passes.

### 5. Functionality

**What it catches:** Dead-end user flows, undefined state transitions, missing screens in multi-step flows, edge cases in conditional paths, flows that work in isolation but break when called as subflows.

**Primary signal:** A user tries to do something the spec allows and hits a wall.

**When it matters most:** Screen flows, portal-facing components, multi-step processes, any build that orchestrates multiple subflows or LWC components.

